      <h5>Top 10 Criteria for Quality of Information on the Web</h5>
      <p>
        In my opinion, the following criteria are the top 10 (in order of importance) for determining 
        the quality of information on the Web. Note: Many criteria are combined because I lay equal importance
        on the qualities being present simultaneously.
      </p>
      <ul class="quality-criteria">
        <li class="criterion">
          <h6>Availability + Accessibility + Openness</h6>
          <p>To be of value, the information should be actually available and accessible. Not all data are available
          on-line, and the information should be easily retrievable when it is needed.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="criterion">
          <h6>Authority + Provenance + Verifiability</h6>
          <p>The information should indicate its source, that depicts the expertise or reputation of its provider.
          The validity of the information should be verifiable irrespective of how authoritative the source is.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="criterion">
          <h6>Accuracy</h6>
          <p>The information should be correct, and should cite sources as support for evidence.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="criterion">
          <h6>Objectivity + Validity</h6>
          <p>The information should not be biased towards a particular object or community, and should provide a fair
          interpretation of facts. The representation should be valid across all uses of the information.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="criterion">
          <h6>Concise Representation + Composition</h6>
          <p>The information should be clear, compact and unambiguous, and the message should have and presented 
          in a coherent, logically sequential manner.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="criterion">
          <h6>Timeliness + Currency</h6>
          <p>The information should indicate over what period the data was collected, when were the data last updated,
          and how long the data is likely to remain current and valid.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="criterion">
          <h6>Scope of Coverage + Relevancy</h6>
          <p>The information should explore a topic over a reasonable extent to be useful. Incomplete analysis often
          degrades quality. Information should not relate to something for which it wasn't intended.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="criterion">
          <h6>Completeness + Documentation</h6>
          <p>All eligible data should be considered for compiling the information, and instructions should be provided
          as to how to interpret individual pieces of information.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="criterion">
          <h6>Reliability + Reputation</h6>
          <p>Users of the information should be able to rely on it for their tasks, and it should not stand invalidated
          in any particular case. It should also indicate its usefulness int he form of user reviews.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="criterion">
          <h6>Usability + Interpretability + Reproducibility</h6>
          <p>Last of all, the information should be able to be interpreted and analysed, to be put into use. It should
          also be capable of achieving a consistent result in all uses.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </article>
